    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-09-27T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-09-27T02:00:00-05:00" n="18"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d18">
                <head>18. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Cambodia</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d18fn1">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 790.5/9–2758. Confidential. Repeated to Bangkok.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Phnom Penh</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1958-09-27T14:00:00+07:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">September 27, 1958—2 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>401. Reference my G–40,<note n="2" xml:id="d18fn2">included in <ref
                            target="frus1958-60v15-16mSupp1">the microfiche supplement</ref>.</note>
                    Department telegram 216,<note n="3" xml:id="d18fn3">Not printed.</note> and
                    memorandum conversation <persName corresp="#p_KEH1">Kellogg</persName> with
                    Australian Minister Stuart, dated August 12, Part 3.<note n="4" xml:id="d18fn4"
                        >Not found.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I have just received from Stuart extract memorandum conversation <persName
                        corresp="#p_NSP1">Sihanouk</persName> with Plimsoll, Assistant Secretary
                    Australian Department External Affairs, dated March 21, 1956.<note n="5"
                        xml:id="d18fn5">Transmitted to the Department as the attachment to despatch
                        113 from Phnom Penh, September 29. (Department of State, Central Files,
                        790.5/9–2958)</note> Memorandum makes clear that <persName corresp="#p_NSP1"
                        >Sihanouk</persName> stated specifically he “not anti-<gloss
                        target="#t_SEATO1">SEATO</gloss>” and that if Cambodia were attacked by
                    Communists “<persName corresp="#p_NSP1">Sihanouk</persName> hoped Cambodia would
                    have <gloss target="#t_SEATO1">SEATO</gloss> help.” <persName corresp="#p_NSP1"
                        >Sihanouk</persName> and Plimsoll agreed that if <gloss target="#t_SEATO1"
                        >SEATO</gloss> did not make statements re importance <gloss
                        target="#t_SEATO1">SEATO</gloss> protection to Cambodia, Cambodia would not
                    attack <gloss target="#t_SEATO1">SEATO</gloss>, and that “less said by either
                    side the better.”</p>
                <p>On September 24 Cambodian National Radio broadcast “editorial” attacking Thailand
                    calls Thai government “puppets entirely sold to foreign imperialists which are
                    carrying on ridiculous anti-Communist campaign.” Editorial then refers to
                    foreign imperialists as “undertaking their policy of war in Asia under form of
                        <gloss target="#t_SEATO1">SEATO</gloss>.” While I still agree probably
                    undesirable to raise question <gloss target="#t_SEATO1">SEATO</gloss> with
                        <persName corresp="#p_NSP1">SIHANOUK</persName>, above information supplied
                    in case matter is raised either with Prince or <persName corresp="#p_SS2">Son
                        Sann</persName>.<note n="6" xml:id="d18fn6">Governor of the National Bank of
                        Cambodia.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SCW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Strom</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
